---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is the difference between ResourceQuota and LimitRange?", answer: "ResourceQuota applies at the namespace level — it sets a total budget for all pods/containers in the namespace combined. For example, 'this namespace cannot use more than 10 CPU cores total'. LimitRange applies at the individual pod/container level — it sets default requests/limits and min/max bounds per container. They complement each other: ResourceQuota prevents a namespace from consuming too many cluster resources; LimitRange ensures every container has sane requests/limits (so ResourceQuota accounting works correctly — containers without requests don't count toward quota)." },
  { question: "What happens if a pod exceeds its namespace ResourceQuota?", answer: "When you try to create a pod (or Deployment that creates pods) that would cause the namespace to exceed its ResourceQuota, the API server rejects the creation with a 'forbidden: exceeded quota' error. Existing pods are not affected — quotas are only enforced at creation time. This means a quota change that makes existing usage exceed the new limit won't evict running pods, but will block new pods from being scheduled." },
  { question: "Why do containers without resource requests break ResourceQuota?", answer: "ResourceQuota tracks CPU and memory by summing the requests of all pods in the namespace. If a container has no requests set, its contribution to the quota count is zero — meaning it's invisible to quota accounting but still uses real resources. This defeats the purpose of quota. The solution is to always use LimitRange with default requests, which automatically injects requests into containers that don't specify them, making quota accounting accurate." },
  { question: "What namespace design patterns work best for multi-team clusters?", answer: "Three common patterns: (1) Per-team namespaces — each team gets their own namespace with ResourceQuota matching their allocation. Simple isolation, easy chargeback. (2) Per-environment namespaces — dev/staging/production per application, with tighter quotas for dev. (3) Hybrid — per-team namespaces that contain per-environment sub-paths. Most organizations start with per-team and add per-environment as they scale. Use Network Policies alongside quotas for complete isolation." },
  { question: "How do I calculate the right ResourceQuota values for my team?", answer: "Start by running kubectl top pods across your existing workloads for a week to get actual usage baselines. Add 30-50% headroom for traffic spikes and deployments. For CPU: sum all container CPU requests + 40% headroom. For memory: sum all container memory requests + 30% headroom. For pods: count current pods × 2 to allow rolling deployments. Review and adjust quotas quarterly as usage changes." },
  { question: "Can ResourceQuota limit other objects besides CPU and memory?", answer: "Yes. ResourceQuota can limit: count/pods, count/services, count/configmaps, count/secrets, count/persistentvolumeclaims, count/deployments.apps, requests.storage (total PVC storage), and more. For example, setting count/secrets: 50 prevents a namespace from having more than 50 Secrets — useful for preventing secret sprawl. You can also set quotas for specific storage classes (e.g., requests.storage for fast-ssd only)." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Kubernetes ResourceQuota & LimitRange: Namespace Resource Guide"
  description="Learn how to configure Kubernetes ResourceQuota and LimitRange for namespace resource management. Per-team and per-environment patterns, default container limits, and quota troubleshooting."
  tool="Kubernetes ResourceQuota, LimitRange, namespace quota, pod resource limits, kubectl get quota"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","name":"Kubernetes ResourceQuota & LimitRange: Namespace Resource Guide","url":"https://devplaybook.cc/tools/k8s-namespace-quota-estimator","description":"Configure Kubernetes ResourceQuota and LimitRange for namespace resource management with per-team and per-environment patterns."})} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Kubernetes ResourceQuota &amp; LimitRange: Namespace Resource Guide</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">ResourceQuota and LimitRange are the two primary tools for controlling resource consumption in Kubernetes namespaces. Together they implement fair-share resource allocation across teams and environments.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> ResourceQuota vs LimitRange</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Namespace design patterns</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Default container limits</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> kubectl get quota</span>
  </div>

  <ToolPageCta />

  <div class="space-y-8 mt-8">

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">ResourceQuota vs LimitRange</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-surface">
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Dimension</th>
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">ResourceQuota</th>
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">LimitRange</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Scope</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Entire namespace (aggregate)</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Per pod / per container</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-surface/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Enforces</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Total CPU, memory, pod count</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Min/max per container, defaults</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Injects defaults?</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">No</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Yes (defaultRequest / default)</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-surface/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Error when exceeded</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Pod creation rejected</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Pod creation rejected</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2 font-medium">Typical use</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Team/env budget allocation</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Sane container defaults</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">ResourceQuota Configuration</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">A ResourceQuota applies aggregate limits to a namespace. All resource counts are tracked by summing container requests.</p>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>apiVersion: v1
kind: ResourceQuota
metadata:
  name: team-alpha-quota
  namespace: team-alpha
spec:
  hard:
    # Compute resources
    requests.cpu: "8"           # Total CPU requests: 8 cores
    requests.memory: 16Gi       # Total memory requests: 16 GiB
    limits.cpu: "16"            # Total CPU limits: 16 cores
    limits.memory: 32Gi         # Total memory limits: 32 GiB

    # Object count limits
    count/pods: "50"
    count/services: "20"
    count/configmaps: "30"
    count/secrets: "50"
    count/persistentvolumeclaims: "10"

    # Storage
    requests.storage: 100Gi</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Checking Quota Usage</h3>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># View quota and current usage
kubectl get resourcequota -n team-alpha
kubectl describe resourcequota team-alpha-quota -n team-alpha

# Example output:
# Resource            Used    Hard
# --------            ----    ----
# count/pods          12      50
# limits.cpu          6       16
# limits.memory       8Gi     32Gi
# requests.cpu        3       8
# requests.memory     4Gi     16Gi</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">LimitRange Configuration</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">LimitRange enforces per-container (and per-pod) resource boundaries and injects defaults for containers that don't specify requests/limits. This is critical for making ResourceQuota accounting work — containers without requests contribute zero to quota sums.</p>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code>apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: team-alpha-limits
  namespace: team-alpha
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    default:
      cpu: "500m"         # Default limit if not specified
      memory: "512Mi"
    defaultRequest:
      cpu: "100m"         # Default request if not specified
      memory: "128Mi"
    max:
      cpu: "4"            # No container can request more than 4 cores
      memory: "8Gi"
    min:
      cpu: "50m"          # Minimum to prevent zero-request containers
      memory: "64Mi"

  - type: Pod
    max:
      cpu: "8"            # Pod total cannot exceed 8 cores
      memory: "16Gi"</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Namespace Design Patterns</h2>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Pattern 1: Per-Team Namespaces</h3>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">Each team gets a dedicated namespace with their own quota. Clean isolation, easy chargeback. Best for organizations with 3-10 teams.</p>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Create per-team namespace with quota
kubectl create namespace team-backend
kubectl create namespace team-frontend
kubectl create namespace team-data

# Apply different quotas per team based on their workloads
kubectl apply -f backend-quota.yaml -n team-backend
kubectl apply -f frontend-quota.yaml -n team-frontend</code></pre>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Pattern 2: Per-Environment Namespaces</h3>
      <p class="text-text-muted mb-3">Separate namespaces for dev, staging, and production per application. Tighter quotas in dev to avoid wasted resources.</p>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Naming convention: {app}-{environment}
# myapp-dev    → small quota (dev work)
# myapp-staging → medium quota
# myapp-prod   → full quota + PDB

kubectl create namespace myapp-dev
kubectl create namespace myapp-staging
kubectl create namespace myapp-prod</code></pre>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-4">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-surface">
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Pattern</th>
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Pros</th>
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Cons</th>
              <th class="border border-border px-3 py-2 text-left font-semibold">Best for</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Per-team</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Simple, easy chargeback</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">No env isolation</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Small orgs</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-surface/30"><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Per-environment</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Env isolation, RBAC clarity</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Namespace sprawl</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Regulated industries</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Hybrid</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Full isolation</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Complex, many namespaces</td><td class="border border-border px-3 py-2">Large enterprises</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Troubleshooting Quota Issues</h2>
      <pre class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg p-4 text-sm font-mono overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code># Pod stuck in Pending? Check quota events
kubectl describe pod my-pod -n team-alpha
# Events: Warning FailedCreate ... exceeded quota: team-alpha-quota

# Check which resource is exhausted
kubectl describe resourcequota -n team-alpha

# Check LimitRange defaults being applied
kubectl describe limitrange -n team-alpha

# See all namespace resource usage
kubectl top pods -n team-alpha --containers</code></pre>
    </section>

  </div>

  <FaqSection faqs={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
